Partial differential equations (PDEs) are equations involving unknown functions of multiple variables and their partial derivatives. Numerical methods transform these continuous problems into discrete algebraic systems that can be solved by computers. The most common methods include the **Finite Difference Method (FDM)**, which approximates derivatives by differecnt quotients on a grid, converting the PDE into a system of algebraic equations; the **Finite Element Method (FEM)**, which divides the domain into smaller subdomains (elements) and approximates the solution using basis functions (often polynomials), minimizing an energy functional or using weighted residuals (Galerkin method); and the **Finite Volume Method (FVM)**, which integrates the PDE over control volumes, applying the divergence theorem to convert volume integrals to surface fluxes, ensuring conservation laws are satisfied locally and globally. Other methods include Spectral Methods, which approximate solutions as sums of global basis functions (like Fourier series) for high accuracy on simple domains, and Boundary Element Methods (BEM), which reduce the problem dimension by formulating it only on the boundary. Stability, consistency, and convergence are critical theoretical aspects ensuring the numerical solution approaches the true solution as the grid refines.
